                            <comment id="13485435" author="chetanm" created="Sat, 27 Oct 2012 14:00:39 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Fixed in Rev. 1402797&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Import instructions before change&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;  ...
  org.apache.tika                       {version=[1.0,2), resolution:=optional}
  org.apache.tika.exception             {version=[1.0,2), resolution:=optional}
  org.osgi.framework                    {version=[1.5,2), resolution:=optional}
  org.osgi.util.tracker                 {version=[1.4,2), resolution:=optional}
  org.slf4j   
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;After fix&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;  ...
  org.apache.lucene.util                {resolution:=optional}
  org.apache.tika                       {version=[1.0,2), resolution:=optional}
  org.apache.tika.exception             {version=[1.0,2), resolution:=optional}
  org.osgi.framework                    {version=[1.5,2)}
  org.osgi.util.tracker                 {version=[1.4,2)}
  org.slf4j                             {version=[1.6,2)}
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13485441" author="chetanm" created="Sat, 27 Oct 2012 14:03:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Issued fixed in Rev 1402797&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13485917" author="tmueller" created="Mon, 29 Oct 2012 09:48:44 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m not sure, does it mean that in order to use Jackrabbit Oak, you will need to have the OSGi jar files in the classpath, even if your application doesn&apos;t itself use OSGi? I guess that wouldn&apos;t be much of a problem&lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/images/icons/emoticons/help_16.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;, as long as the application isn&apos;t forced to use OSGi.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13485936" author="chetanm" created="Mon, 29 Oct 2012 10:27:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;No you would not require OSGi jars in classpath for non OSGi usecases as provided scope dependencies are not transitive&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13485953" author="tmueller" created="Mon, 29 Oct 2012 10:58:42 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for the clarification! &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
